<% content_for :title, "Styleguide" %>

<div class="sg">
  <h1>üsgu styleguide</h1>
  <p class="sg-lede">
    A living reference: every specimen below is the real shared element class,
    rendered with the same bundled CSS as the rest of the app — so it stays in
    sync as the styles change. Each entry states the <b>one purpose</b> the
    element should telegraph. Numbers cross-reference <code>docs/ui-audit.md</code>;
    amber notes flag a remaining drift, green notes mark what this
    <b>experimental redesign</b> branch resolved.
  </p>
  <p class="sg-lede">
    Palette: a <b>dirty-cream ground + green</b> (light theme; dark theme keeps the
    aubergine ground + brighter green). On-accent text matches the background for a
    "punched out" button. <b>Green is the dominant accent</b> — interaction (links,
    focus, primary), state (today, selected) <b>and follows</b> (the green star) —
    so it's present everywhere. <b>Raspberry is rare</b>: the "saved show" heart
    only. The two personal signals differ in colour AND shape (green star = follow,
    raspberry heart = saved), never colour alone. Structural rules use a neutral
    hairline (<code>--border-color</code>) or content divider (<code>--rule-color</code>).
    One <code>danger</code> language (hollow → fills), one Phosphor disclosure caret,
    a baseline <code>:focus-visible</code> ring, and a display-only <code>.icon</code>
    role beside the clickable <code>.icon-button</code>.
  </p>

  <nav class="sg-toc">
    <a href="#colours">Colour intent</a>
    <a href="#buttons">Buttons &amp; actions</a>
    <a href="#pills">Pills, badges &amp; chips</a>
    <a href="#dropdowns">Dropdowns &amp; selects</a>
    <a href="#inputs">Form inputs</a>
    <a href="#icons">Icons</a>
    <a href="#nav">Navigation</a>
  </nav>

  <%# ============================================================ COLOURS %>
  <section class="sg-section" id="colours">
    <h2>Colour intent</h2>
    <p class="sg-section__intro">
      Each semantic token should carry exactly one meaning. Swatches read live
      from the theme tokens (toggle the theme to see dark values).
    </p>
    <ul class="sg-swatches">
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--accent"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Accent</b> · <code>--theme-accent-color</code><br>The dominant accent: interaction (links, focus, primary), state (today, selected), <b>and follows</b> (the green star + followed tags)</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--accent-mut"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Accent muted</b> · <code>--theme-accent-muted</code><br>Quiet accent ground (window chips)</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--on-accent"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>On accent</b> · <code>--theme-on-accent</code><br>Text/glyphs painted ON the accent fill (primary buttons, badges, today, ticks). Set to the page background (<code>--theme-bg-color</code>) for the "punched out" look — legible because each theme pairs a light-ish ground with a dark-enough green (cream-on-green in light, plum-on-green in dark).</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--favorite"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Saved</b> · <code>--theme-saved-color</code><br>Raspberry — the rare, powerful "saved show" highlight (the heart) only. NOT follows (those are green). One emphatic colour, used sparingly.</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--warn"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Warn</b> · <code>--theme-warn-color</code><br>Destructive / error only</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--amber"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Amber</b> · <code>--color-amber</code><br>Neutral "empty / nothing here" status</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--bg"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Background</b> · <code>--theme-bg-color</code></p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--bg-mut"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Background muted</b> · <code>--theme-bg-muted</code><br>Neutral fills + the sand highlight wash shared by dropdown options and the calendar day hover/selected</p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--fg"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Foreground</b> · <code>--theme-fg-color</code></p>
      </li>
      <li class="sg-swatch">
        <div class="sg-swatch__chip sg-swatch__chip--fg-mut"></div>
        <p class="sg-swatch__label"><b>Foreground muted</b> · <code>--theme-fg-muted</code><br>Secondary text, at-rest chrome/icons</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="sg-ok">
      <b>Audit #1 / #10 — resolved.</b> Structural borders, the nav-menu panel,
      raw <code>input</code> text, and the filter-handle icon are neutral
      (<code>--border-color</code> / <code>--rule-color</code> /
      <code>--theme-fg-muted</code>). Field underlines use a more present neutral
      (<code>--field-border-color</code>) so an empty input reads as fillable, and
      the calendar grid its own (<code>--calendar-border-color</code>) so it reads
      as a grid on the saturated ground — both still neutral, derived from the
      foreground. Green appears on a field only on focus, and otherwise only for
      links, active state, primary actions, and follows.
    </p>
  </section>

  <%# ============================================================ BUTTONS %>
  <section class="sg-section" id="buttons">
    <h2>Buttons &amp; actions</h2>
    <p class="sg-section__intro"><b>Three weights:</b> primary → secondary → danger, plus the flat icon action and the text link. Weight is the role; size (full-width vs small pill) is just context, not a separate tier. <b>Per-page primary:</b> at most one filled button per page, so it's the thing that stands out — everything else is secondary (hollow) or danger.</p>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <input type="submit" value="Save">
        <button type="button" class="button-small primary">Done</button>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Primary</span> · <code>input[type=submit]</code> / <code>.primary</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">The ONE main commit of a page — filled accent. <code>input[type=submit]</code> is primary automatically; a non-submit primary (the rule editor's done link, the cookie CTA) opts in with <code>.primary</code> at any size.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <button type="button" class="button">Enable</button>
        <button type="button" class="button-small">Test now</button>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Secondary</span> · <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> / <code>.button</code> / <code>.button-small</code> (default)
        <p class="sg-purpose">Every action that isn't the page's primary or destructive — hollow accent, full-size or pill. One treatment (no separate "neutral box" vs "ghost"): Sign out, Enable, Test now, Pause, Create link, …</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Resolved.</b> Collapsed the old neutral-box + secondary-filled-pill + tertiary-ghost into one secondary look; primary is now filled-only and rare. (The transitional <code>.button-ghost</code> no-op alias has since been removed — the markup is fully swept.)</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <button type="button" class="button-small danger">Delete rule</button>
        <span class="account-form"><button type="button" class="button delete">Delete account</button></span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Danger</span> · <code>.button-small.danger</code> &nbsp;/&nbsp; <code>.button.delete</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">A destructive, hard-to-undo action. Hollow warn at rest; fills warn on hover/focus.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #2 — resolved.</b> Both now share one danger language (hollow → fills); the only difference is size (full-width vs pill). Hover a specimen to see the fill.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <a href="#buttons" class="icon-button" aria-label="Edit"><span class="ph ph-gear"></span></a>
        <button type="button" class="icon-button danger" aria-label="Delete"><span class="ph ph-trash"></span></button>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Icon button</span> · <code>.icon-button</code>, <code>.icon-button.danger</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">A flat, boxless inline icon action on a row (edit gear, delete trash). Muted at rest → foreground on hover; danger → warn on hover.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen"><a href="#buttons" class="text-link">Open filter</a></div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Text link</span> · <code>.text-link</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Navigation ("go somewhere else") rendered as an underlined accent link — distinct from in-place action buttons. Borderless: it's a link, not a control box.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen"><button type="button" class="theme-toggle" aria-label="Theme"><span class="ph ph-moon"></span></button></div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Theme toggle</span> · <code>.theme-toggle</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Icon-only accent button; toggles light ↔ dark.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="view-switcher" style="display:inline-flex; gap:var(--gap-medium);">
          <a href="#buttons" class="view-switch__item">List</a>
          <a href="#buttons" class="view-switch__item active"><b>Calendar</b></a>
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">View switcher</span> · <code>.view-switch__item</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Flat text toggle (not a button) between list and calendar; active = bold accent. The flat-text controls (view switcher, favorites + notify shortcuts) use their own domain classes rather than borrowing <code>.button</code>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <input type="submit" value="Disabled" disabled>
        <button type="button" class="button-small" disabled>Disabled</button>
        <a href="#buttons" class="button-small">Focus me (Tab)</a>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">States</span> · <code>:disabled</code>, <code>:focus-visible</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Disabled = 0.5 opacity + not-allowed cursor. Tab to any control to see the shared accent focus ring.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #12 — resolved.</b> Baseline <code>:focus-visible</code> ring on all interactive elements; <code>:disabled</code> on buttons and pills.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# ============================================================ PILLS %>
  <section class="sg-section" id="pills">
    <h2>Pills, badges &amp; chips</h2>
    <p class="sg-section__intro"><b>Governing rule: a box reads as clickable.</b> Buttons are the only bordered/filled boxes — so anything with a border or solid fill says "do something", and <b>information carries no border/fill</b> (a faint tint at most). That's how you tell a read-only channel pill from a ghost action button at a glance.</p>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="chip">In-app</span>
        <span class="chip chip--window">Mon–Sun</span>
        <span class="chip chip--type">New events</span>
        <span class="chip chip--muted">Disabled</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Info chip</span> · <code>.chip</code> (<code>--window</code>, <code>--type</code>, <code>--muted</code>)
        <p class="sg-purpose">Read-only metadata that is never clickable (channels, windows, rule type, disabled state).</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Resolved.</b> Now borderless (faint tint), so it no longer reads like a ghost action button. Border/fill is reserved for things you can click.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="badge">3</span>
        <span class="badge">+2 more</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Count badge</span> · <code>.badge</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">A small accent count attached to something else (unread notifications, "+N more").</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #8 — resolved.</b> The mobile filter trigger now uses this same <code>.badge</code>; the duplicate <code>.filter-trigger__badge</code> is gone.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="tag">Techno</span>
        <span class="tag active">Jazz</span>
        <button type="button" class="tag">Ambient</button>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Selectable tag</span> · <code>.tag</code>, <code>.tag.active</code>, <code>button.tag</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">A style/query token. <code>.active</code> (filled accent) = the currently-selected / current option (e.g. a status filter). <b>No ×</b> — it's a state, not removable.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #5 — resolved.</b> Removable applied-filters now carry a trailing × (<code>.tag__remove</code>, like the filter chip below); a selected-state <code>.tag.active</code> has none. The × is the tell: <b>× = remove me</b>, no × = current selection.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <button type="button" class="filter-chip">
          <span class="filter-chip__icon ph ph-music-notes"></span>
          <span class="filter-chip__label">Jazz</span>
          <span class="filter-chip__remove ph ph-x" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </button>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Applied filter chip</span> · <code>.filter-chip</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">An active filter on the mobile summary row; tapping it removes that one value.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #12 — resolved.</b> Now dims on hover/focus to signal the "× to remove" affordance.</span>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #5 — resolved.</b> The inline desktop filter's applied tokens now carry the same trailing × — so removable filters read consistently across desktop and mobile, and distinctly from a selected-state <code>.tag.active</code>.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="tag active" data-tag-chip><span class="ph ph-map-trifold" aria-hidden="true"></span><span>BE</span><span class="tag__remove ph ph-x" aria-hidden="true"></span></span>
        <span class="tag active" data-tag-chip><span class="ph ph-map-pin" aria-hidden="true"></span><span>Bern</span><span class="tag__remove ph ph-x" aria-hidden="true"></span></span>
        <span class="tag active" data-tag-chip><span class="ph ph-house" aria-hidden="true"></span><span>Dachstock</span><span class="tag__remove ph ph-x" aria-hidden="true"></span></span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Applied location chip (desktop)</span> · <code>.tag[data-tag-chip]</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">A removable location filter (inline desktop filter + rule editor). The leading icon is <b>per type</b> — canton <code>map-trifold</code> / city <code>map-pin</code> / venue <code>house</code> — not a flat pin, matching the dropdown and mobile sheet.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Resolved.</b> The × inherits the label colour (no longer pre-dimmed); the whole chip dims on hover/focus to telegraph "tap to remove". Resolved server-side (<code>filter_chip_icon</code> reads the value's type) — no location list shipped to JS.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="scrape-badge scrape-badge--ok">OK</span>
        <span class="scrape-badge scrape-badge--empty">No results</span>
        <span class="scrape-badge scrape-badge--failed">2 failed</span>
        <span class="scrape-badge scrape-badge--running">Running</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Status badge</span> · <code>.scrape-badge--{ok,empty,failed,running}</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Scrape outcome, encoded by hue (green/amber/red/grey). The one place a solid green pill means "success" rather than "primary/selected".</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# ============================================================ DROPDOWNS %>
  <section class="sg-section" id="dropdowns">
    <h2>Dropdowns &amp; selects</h2>
    <p class="sg-section__intro">Disclosure indicators currently use three different glyph systems (audit #3). Specimens shown with the real account-form treatment.</p>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="account-form">
          <select aria-label="Language">
            <option value="" selected>Choose a language…</option>
            <option>German</option><option>French</option><option>English</option>
          </select>
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Styled select</span> · <code>.account-form select</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">An underline field with a chevron, matching the form fields. Neutral underline at rest, accent on focus.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #3 / #11 — resolved.</b> The chevron is now a neutral mid-grey that reads on both themes (was a hard-coded <code>#0e8857</code> that stayed green in dark mode).</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <details class="nav-menu">
          <summary>account</summary>
          <div class="nav-menu__items">
            <a href="#nav">Settings</a>
            <a href="#nav">Log out</a>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Menu dropdown</span> · <code>.nav-menu</code> (<code>&lt;details&gt;</code>)
        <p class="sg-purpose">Collapses account links into a bordered panel; the summary is the trigger.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #3 — resolved.</b> Now uses the shared Phosphor caret (mask + <code>currentColor</code>) that rotates on open — same glyph as the select and filter triggers (was a Unicode <code>▾</code>).</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# ============================================================ INPUTS %>
  <section class="sg-section" id="inputs">
    <h2>Form inputs</h2>
    <p class="sg-section__intro">Two intentional field skins — underline (forms) and borderless-grow (filter bar) — plus three checkbox implementations (audit #4).</p>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="account-form" style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:var(--gap-small);">
          <span class="field-label">Field label</span>
          <span class="muted">A short hint — muted and smaller.</span>
          <input type="text" placeholder="value / input" aria-label="Field">
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Field label / value / hint</span> · <code>.field-label</code> + <code>.muted</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">One typographic ladder per form field, in reading order: a <b>bold</b> <code>.field-label</code> (a <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> over a value/select, or a fieldset <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code>), then a muted, smaller <code>.muted</code> hint, then the normal-weight value/input — so the hint is read <em>before</em> you fill the field, not after. The section <code>h2</code> is larger so it stays the heading. Every label in a section uses this one style — don't let them drift into mixed weights (bold legend vs muted span vs plain span).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="account-form" style="display:flex; gap:var(--gap-medium); flex-wrap:wrap;">
          <input type="text" placeholder="Username" aria-label="Username">
          <input type="password" placeholder="Password" aria-label="Password">
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Account / auth field</span> · <code>.account-form input</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Underline-only field; neutral bottom border, lights accent on focus. Typed text is foreground.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #1 — resolved.</b> Resting underline is neutral and the global <code>input</code> colour is foreground; green now appears only when the field is focused.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <label style="display:inline-flex; gap:var(--gap-small); align-items:center;">
          <input type="checkbox" checked> Native checkbox
        </label>
        <label class="tag">
          <input type="checkbox" checked> Chip checkbox
        </label>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Checkboxes</span> · <code>input[type=checkbox]</code> &nbsp;/&nbsp; <code>label.tag</code> &nbsp;/&nbsp; <code>.opt__box</code> (sheets)
        <p class="sg-purpose">Confirm an opt-in. One custom box (left) is used everywhere; the selectable chip fills accent when checked.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>Audit #4 — resolved.</b> All standalone checkboxes now share one custom box (<code>appearance:none</code>, matching the sheet's <code>.opt__box</code>) — no more native-vs-custom split. The chip (<code>label.tag</code>) stays a distinct, deliberate selectable-chip pattern.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# ============================================================ ICONS %>
  <section class="sg-section" id="icons">
    <h2>Icons</h2>
    <p class="sg-section__intro">Phosphor Regular (base class <code>ph</code>); the follow <b>star</b> and saved <b>heart</b> are masked SVGs (outline→fill for off/on state). Clickable icons use <code>.icon-button</code>; display-only icons use the <code>.icon</code> role (audit #9, resolved).</p>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen" style="font-size:1.4rem;">
        <span class="icon ph ph-calendar-dots"></span>
        <span class="icon ph ph-map-pin"></span>
        <span class="filter-icon ph ph-magnifying-glass"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Display icon</span> · <code>.icon</code> (muted) · <code>.filter-icon</code> (green)
        <p class="sg-purpose">A non-interactive metadata glyph is muted (<code>.icon</code>, the counterpart to the clickable <code>.icon-button</code>). <b>Exception:</b> a filter field's leading handle (<code>.filter-icon</code> / <code>.filter-trigger__icon</code>, the green one) is accent-green — the field opens a dropdown/picker, so the glyph reads as an interactive affordance, not passive decoration.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen" style="font-size:1.4rem;">
        <span class="ph ph-gear" title="ph-gear"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-trash" title="ph-trash"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-bell" title="ph-bell"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-x" title="ph-x"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-magnifying-glass" title="ph-magnifying-glass"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-caret-down" title="ph-caret-down"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-map-pin" title="ph-map-pin"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-house" title="ph-house"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-map-trifold" title="ph-map-trifold"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-music-notes" title="ph-music-notes"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-tag" title="ph-tag"></span>
        <span class="ph ph-calendar-dots" title="ph-calendar-dots"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Glyph set</span> · <code>.ph .ph-*</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">Hover a glyph to see its name. Edit, delete, notify, close/remove, search, disclosure, city/venue/canton, style/genre, date. (Follow/save use the masked star/heart below, not a font glyph.)</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen">
        <span class="save-filter-link"><span class="save-filter-icon"><span class="ph ph-funnel" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class="save-filter-plus" aria-hidden="true">+</span></span></span>
        <span class="save-filter-link active"><span class="funnel-fill" aria-hidden="true"></span></span>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Save-filter funnel</span> · <code>.save-filter-link</code>, <code>.funnel-fill</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">"Save this filter" — pinned by the applied-filter chips. Outline funnel + <b>+</b> = not saved (opens the editor with the current filter as a draft); solid <b>green</b> funnel = saved (opens the saved filter's editor). Shares the funnel metaphor with the nav "Filter" section; notification channels live in the editor, not here.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sg-row">
      <div class="sg-specimen" style="font-size:1.4rem;">
        <button type="button" class="event-save icon-button" aria-label="Save"><span class="save-heart"></span></button>
        <button type="button" class="event-save icon-button saved" aria-label="Saved"><span class="save-heart"></span></button>
      </div>
      <div class="sg-spec">
        <span class="sg-spec__name">Save heart</span> · <code>.save-heart</code>
        <p class="sg-purpose">"Save this show" — the rare, powerful signal. Faint outline = not saved; solid <b>raspberry</b> = saved.</p>
        <span class="sg-ok"><b>The two personal signals:</b> save filter = green <b>star</b>, save show = raspberry <b>heart</b>. Distinct in colour AND shape, so neither relies on colour alone. Both use outline→fill for off/on.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

